	volume = {98},
	abstract = {The red-legged partridge (Alectoris rufa) is the only indigenous Alectoris species in the Iberian Peninsula. Local populations are often reinforced with captive-bred individuals, sometimes including hybrids between the red-legged partridge and the exotic rock partridge (A. graeca). Hunters and wildlife managers oppose releases of hybrids, but their identi®cation by visual inspection is dif®cult beyond the ®rst hybrid generation. Here we report the development of a set of RAPD markers to identify hybrid partridges using blood samples. We initially screened 46 RAPD primers on a subsample of pure red-legged and rock partridges, and ®nally selected six primers that produced 11 markers speci®c of the rock partridge. The selected primers were tested on hybrids of dierent generations bred in captivity. This set of loci permitted the detection of 100\% (n=31) F1 hybrids, 100\% (n=14) backcrosses of F1 to red-legged partridge, all but one (95\%, n=18) hybrid of the second backcross, and 18 out of 27 (67\%, n=27) hybrids of the third backcross. Ecient detection of backcross 1 and 2 individuals is essential, as these are the ones released for re-stocking purposes in hunting states. Although we have only used blood samples, other sources of high-quality DNA, such as muscle, should provide the same results. Therefore, it would be feasible to monitor the genetic purity of partridges in farms and hunting states at dierent stages of production, including embryos, chicks or hunted specimens. \# 2001 Elsevier Science Ltd. All rights reserved.},
